---
import DocsLayout from "~/layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import Code from "~/components/Code.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Syntax" current="syntax" description="The lexical and structural syntax of a kex program.">
  <h1>Syntax</h1>

  <p>
    Kex borrows Ruby’s <code>do … end</code> blocks and identifier conventions,
    layers on type annotations with <code>:</code>, and uses <code>-&gt;</code>
    for return types and <code>=</code> for expression-bodied functions.
  </p>

  <h2>Comments</h2>
  <Code code={`# this is a line comment`} bare compact />

  <h2>Bindings</h2>
  <p>
    <code>let</code> binds an immutable name. <code>var</code> opts into local
    mutation. The <code>!</code> suffix rebinds a <code>var</code> to a
    method’s updated return value.
  </p>
  <Code code={`let name = "kex"          # immutable
var count = 0             # mutable
count = count + 1         # reassign

var list = [1, 2, 3]
list.push!(4)             # list := list.push(4)`} file="bindings.kex" source="examples/bindings.kex" />

  <h2>Functions</h2>
  <p>
    A function is either a single expression after <code>=</code>, or a
    <code>do … end</code> block ending in <code>return</code>.
  </p>
  <Code code={`let double(n: Integer) = n * 2

let greet(name: String) -> String do
  return "Hello, \${name}!"
end

let add(a, b) = a + b   # types can be inferred`} file="functions.kex" source="examples/functions.kex" />

  <h2>Blocks and lambdas</h2>
  <Code code={`[1, 2, 3].map { |x| x * 2 }

[1, 2, 3].each do |x|
  IO.printLine(x.to(String))
end`} file="blocks.kex" source="examples/blocks.kex" />

  <h2>Records and construction</h2>
  <Code code={`record Point do
  x : Float
  y : Float
end

let p = Point { x: 1.0, y: 2.0 }`} file="point.kex" source="examples/point.kex" />

  <h2>Control flow</h2>
  <p>
    Branching is <code>if / elif / else</code>, optionally with a trailing
    <code>if</code> guard. Rich dispatch lives in <a href="/docs/pattern-matching"><code>match</code></a>.
  </p>
  <Code code={`return Error(EmptyInput) if s.empty?

if n > 0
  "positive"
elif n < 0
  "negative"
else
  "zero"
end`} file="control.kex" source="examples/control.kex" />

  <h2>String interpolation</h2>
  <Code code={`let name = "world"
"Hello, \${name}!"
"\${(1..3).sum}"   # "6"`} file="interp.kex" source="examples/interp.kex" />
</DocsLayout>
